
"Predicting Breast Cancer Diagnosis Using Machine Learning"
"Milestone 1 Report: Dataset Selection & Data Preprocessing"
""
"Problem Statement"
"Breast cancer diagnosis relies on manual interpretation of cell nuclei features from fine needle aspirate (FNA) images, which is time-consuming and subject to inter-observer variability. This project aims to build a machine learning classification model that predicts whether a breast mass is malignant or benign based on quantitative cell nucleus measurements, supporting faster and more consistent diagnostic decisions."
"Dataset Source & Justification"
"The Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) dataset was used, sourced from the UCI Machine Learning Repository and Kaggle, and also available directly through scikit-learn (sklearn.datasets.load_breast_cancer). It was selected because it is a well-established benchmark for binary medical classification tasks, contains clean numeric features suitable for a range of algorithms, and directly matches the project's proposed goal of diagnostic classification."
