"Preprocessing Steps Performed"
"1) Missing values: none found; verified programmatically, no imputation required. 2) Duplicates: checked with df.duplicated(); none present. 3) Outliers: detected per-feature using the IQR method and capped (winsorized) at the"
"1.5xIQR bounds rather than dropped, preserving sample size. 4) Encoding: target confirmed as numeric (0/1) via LabelEncoder; all other features were already continuous numeric, so no one-hot encoding was needed. 5) Feature scaling: StandardScaler (z-score standardization) applied to all 30 features, since they vary widely in scale/units and several candidate classifiers (Logistic Regression, SVM, KNN) are distance/gradient-sensitive. 6) Class imbalance: distribution is ~63/37, a moderate but non-trivial imbalance; SMOTE-Tomek was applied on the training split only (after train/test split, to avoid leakage) to oversample the minority (malignant) class with synthetic samples and remove ambiguous borderline (Tomek link) pairs, yielding a balanced 50/50 training set."
"Libraries & Tools Used"
"Python, Pandas, NumPy, Scikit-learn, Imbalanced-learn (SMOTE-Tomek), Matplotlib/Seaborn for visualization, Google Colab / Jupyter Notebook, and Git & GitHub for version control."
"Challenges Encountered"
"The dataset was already relatively clean (no missing values or duplicates), so the main challenge was deciding an outlier-treatment strategy that would not shrink the already modest sample size; capping via IQR was chosen over row deletion. Additionally, since the class imbalance was moderate rather than severe, care was taken to apply SMOTE-Tomek only on the training set to avoid inflating test performance through data leakage."
